{{Infobox boxer | name = Orzubek Nazarov | image = | realname = Orzubek Nazarov | nickname = Gussie | nationality = [[Kyrgyzstan]] | weight = [[Lightweight]] | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1966|8|30|mf=y}} | birth_place = [[Kant, Kyrgyzstan|Kant]], [[Kyrgyz SSR]] | died = | style = [[Southpaw (boxing)|Southpaw]] | total = 27 | wins = 26 | KO = 19 | losses = 1 | draws = 0 | no contests = 0 | medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry | {{URS}} }} {{MedalSport | Men’s [[Boxing]]}} {{MedalCompetition|[[World Amateur Boxing Championships|World Amateur Championships]]}} {{MedalBronze| [[1986 World Amateur Boxing Championships|1986 Reno]] | Lightweight}} {{MedalCompetition|[[European Amateur Boxing Championships|European Amateur Championships]]}} {{MedalGold| [[1987 European Amateur Boxing Championships|1987 Turin]] | Lightweight}} }}
'''Orzubek Nazarov''' (born August 30, 1966 in [[Kant, Kyrgyzstan|Kant]], [[Kyrgyz SSR]]) is a boxer of [[Uzbek/Kyrgyz]] ethnicity, who won the bronze medal at the [[1986 World Amateur Boxing Championships]] in [[Reno, Nevada|Reno]]. He is a former [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] Lightweight Champion.
==Career== As an amateur Nazarov was the World bronze medalist in 1986 and European champion in 1987 and had a record of 153-12.
==Pro== The southpaw turned pro in 1990 in Japan, one of the six Amateur Elite boxers (including [[Yuri Arbachakov]]) scouted out of the old [[Soviet Union]] by the [http://www.kyoei-boxing.co.jp/index2 Kyoei Gym]. He won the WBA lightweight title in 1993 in South Africa against [[Dingaan Thobela]] and defended it on the road against contenders Thobela, [[Joey Gamache]] and [[Leavander Johnson]] and two lesser fighters in his adopted home country. Eye problems plagued him and he retired after being upset by [[Jean Baptiste Mendy]] in France.
