{{Infobox bus accident | image = | caption = Location | title = 2015 Puisseguin road crash | time = 07:30 local time (05:30 UTC) | location = [[Puisseguin]] | country = [[France]] | date = 23 October 2015 | deaths = 43 | injuries =8 }}
The ''' 2015 Puisseguin road crash''' occurred on 23 October 2015, at 07:30 local time (05:30 UTC). 43 people,<ref>{{Cite web|title = France coach crash: at least 43 dead after collision with truck|url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/23/at-least-40-dead-after-bus-crash-in-south-of-france-puisseguin|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 2015-10-23|first = Angelique Chrisafis in|last = Paris|first2 = Jessica Elgot in|last2 = London}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = 43 Dead After Bus Carrying Elderly People Collides With Truck|url = http://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/libourne-crash-42-dead-crash-between-bus-truck-france-n449776|website = NBC News|accessdate = 2015-10-23}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title = At least 43 people have died in a coach crash in France|url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/libourne-france-bus-crash-live-dozens-dead-after-coach-and-lorry-accident-near-bordeaux-a6705276.html|website = The Independent|accessdate = 2015-10-23|language = en}}</ref> including a three-year-old boy,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Toddler among 43 dead in French coach crash - The Local|url = http://www.thelocal.fr/20151023/breaking-39-dead-in-coach-crash-in-france|website = www.thelocal.fr|accessdate = 2015-10-23}}</ref> died when a bus and a lorry collided in [[Puisseguin]], a commune in south-western France.<ref name=BBCNews>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-34613637|title=42 people die in a collision between a bus and a lorry in France|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=23 October 2015|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20151023-france-bus-dozens-killed-southwest-puisseguin|title=At least 40 killed as bus collides with truck in southwest France - France 24|date=23 October 2015|publisher=|accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/10/23/us-france-bus-crash-idUSKCN0SH0IQ20151023|title=At least 42 people die in after a bus collide with a lorry|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=23 October 2015|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>
==Crash== The crash happened at around 07:30 on the morning of Friday, 23 October 2015 at a bend on Departmental Road 17 not far south of Puisseguin.<ref name=BBCNews /> Authorities said they believed the lorry, carrying logs, lost control on a bend and [[Jackknifing|jackknifed]] into the coach's path.<ref name=":0" /> Both vehicles burst into flames as a result of the collision.<ref name="lemonde.fr">[http://www.lemonde.fr/police-justice/article/2015/10/23/une-collision-entre-un-camion-et-un-car-fait-42-morts-en-gironde_4795380_1653578.html Report on crash in ''Le Monde'']</ref>
The cause of the fire and consequent loss of life was that the truck had installed on a large aluminum gasoline tank carrying fuel for chainsaws and other logging equipment which ruptured in the crash. Afterwards, gasoline streamed down the hill under the bus, where accident sparks ignited it, and the fire traveled back to the truck.
The bus was equipped with emergency escape hammers with which to break windows, but passengers were not aware of them or not instructed in their use, and several passengers had mobility issues.
==Casualties== Forty-one of the dead were on the bus, with the other two being the driver of the lorry and his three-year-old son. Most of the dead on the bus were elderly people who had just set off from the nearby town of [[Petit-Palais-et-Cornemps]],<ref name=BBCNews /> and belonged to that town's seniors' club.<ref name="lemonde.fr"/>
== Rules ==
According to the [[French Land Transport Accident Investigation Bureau|BEA-TT]], the different applicable rules/standards for road vehicles such as autocar, to address fire concerns, are defined at different scales, to let those vehicles work and operate in various countries: United Nations, European Union, and France. Some European directives have been withdrawal.<ref name="rapport_beatt_2015-014."/>
According to [[Elisabeth Borne]], France submitted the [[French Land Transport Accident Investigation Bureau|BEA-TT]] report to United Nations on 11 October 2017.<ref>http://www.mobilicites.com/011-6547-Puisseguin-l-ONU-va-plancher-sur-l-evolution-de-la-securite-des-autocars.html</ref>
