{{For|the fictional technology from the [[Dune (franchise)|Dune series]]|Suspensor (Dune)}}

'''Suspensors''' are [[Anatomy|anatomical]] structures found in certain [[fungi]] and [[plant]]s.


==Fungi==
In fungi, suspensors are filamentous structural formations having the function of holding a [[zygospore]] between two [[Strain (biology)|strains]] of [[hyphae]].

==Plants==
In plants, suspensors are found in [[zygote]]s in [[angiosperm]]s, connecting the [[endosperm]] to an [[embryo]]. Usually in [[Dicotyledon|dicots]] the suspensor cells divide transversally a few times to form a filamentous suspensor of 6-10 cells. The suspensor helps in pushing the embryo into the endosperm. The first cell of the suspensor towards the micropylar end becomes swollen and functions as a [[haustorium]]. The haustorium has wall ingrowths similar to those of a [[transfer cell]]. The last of the suspensors at the end of the embryo is known as [[hypophysis (plant embryogenesis)|hypophysis]]. Hypophysis later gives rise to the [[radicle]] and root cap. During embryo development in angiosperm seeds, normal development involves asymmetrical division of the unicellular embryo, inducing polarity. The smaller terminal cell divides to become the proembryo while the larger basal cell divides laterally to form the suspensor. The suspensor is analogous to a placental mammalian's [[umbilical cord]].

